Epoch:0 | TOPIC | Scientist1:This is a timely and impactful direction to pursue. Given the rapid proliferation of summarization models—ranging from lightweight extractive systems to large generative transformers—there's growing fragmentation in how summaries are produced, evaluated, and deployed. A key pain point across both industry and academia is the need to adapt or improve outputs from *already-trained* models without retraining, especially when dealing with proprietary or computationally expensive models.

A model-agnostic post-processing framework could serve as a unifying layer that refines summarization outputs based on downstream criteria such as factual consistency, coherence, length constraints, or bias mitigation. The core innovation would lie in designing a framework that operates solely on input text, model output, and optional metadata—without accessing model internals or gradients.

One promising path is leveraging structured intermediate representations (e.g., discourse graphs or semantic frames) to analyze discrepancies between source and summary, then applying lightweight corrective modules—such as sentence reordering, entity realignment, or entailment-guided rewriting—conditioned on these analyses. These modules could be parameterized by small, task-specific models trained independently of the original summarizer.

Crucially, such a framework would enable plug-and-play enhancement: for instance, improving factuality in a black-box commercial summarizer or adapting a general-purpose model to domain-specific needs (e.g., clinical or legal texts) without fine-tuning. This aligns well with emerging trends in modular AI, system efficiency, and responsible deployment.

An open challenge will be defining generalizable metrics for post-hoc evaluation—how do we reliably measure improvement when reference-based scores like ROUGE may not reflect quality gains in faithfulness or readability? Integrating human-aligned reward models or probe-based diagnostics might be essential.

Overall, this approach not only addresses practical deployment barriers but also opens theoretical questions about the separability of generation and refinement in language tasks—a concept with implications beyond summarization.
