Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: My intuition stems from the growing need to decouple post-hoc refinement of abstractive summaries from the underlying summarization models, especially as diverse architectures (e.g., T5, BART, LLaMA-based summarizers) proliferate. While recent work like FactEdit (Paper 3) addresses factual errors via post-editing and REFLEX (Paper 1) introduces rational layers for consistency in QA, none offer a truly dynamic, model-agnostic intervention mechanism that adapts its correction strategy based on both error type and source model behavior. Moreover, interactive systems (Paper 2) show the value of stateful processing but are user-centric rather than model-agnostic. I propose a novel framework—a **dynamic intervention layer**—that sits between any pre-trained summarizer and the final output, dynamically selecting corrective modules conditioned on structured intermediate representations of the summary and source document. This layer does not require retraining the base model or fine-tuning on specific architectures. Instead, it uses lightweight, modular correctors (e.g., for factuality, coherence, redundancy) activated only when needed, guided by an analysis of semantic propositions extracted into a belief-like graph (inspired by REFLEX), but adapted for summarization-specific inconsistencies. Unlike FactEdit, which relies on synthetic error data, our system learns to detect and route corrections using real-time diagnostic signals derived from entailment, coreference, and knowledge grounding. The key novelty lies in the *conditional activation* of specialized post-processors based on interpretable intermediate states, enabling efficient, targeted refinement without cascading errors or unnecessary edits. This approach is more adaptive than static post-editors and more scalable than model-specific fine-tuning.

