  "Idea": "We propose a model-agnostic dynamic intervention layer for post-hoc refinement of abstractive summaries, designed to integrate seamlessly with any pre-trained summarization model without requiring retraining or architectural modifications. The core innovation lies in a two-stage process: (1) constructing a structured intermediate representation (SIR) of the generated summary in relation to the source document, and (2) conditionally activating specialized corrective modules based on diagnostic signals extracted from this representation. The SIR encodes semantic propositions as nodes in a lightweight belief graph, where edges represent inferential relationships such as attribution, temporal order, causal links, and factual grounding. Using off-the-shelf NLI models, entity linking tools, and coreference resolvers, the system populates this graph and identifies potential inconsistencies—such as unsupported claims, contradictory statements, or omitted key entities. A meta-controller, implemented as a shallow router network, evaluates the integrity of the belief graph and determines which corrective module(s) to invoke: e.g., a factuality corrector using language model infilling (inspired by Paper 3), a coherence enhancer that reorders sentences via reinforcement learning (inspired by Paper 2), or a redundancy reducer based on semantic similarity thresholds. Crucially, each module operates independently and is only engaged when its corresponding error signal exceeds a learned threshold, minimizing unintended side effects. The entire framework is trained end-to-end on correction decisions—not on summary generation—using a multi-task dataset annotated for different error types across multiple source models. By decoupling diagnosis from correction and making interventions conditional, our system achieves high precision in refinement while maintaining fluency and relevance. This enables deployment across heterogeneous models—from small fine-tuned BARTs to large LLM-based summarizers—without per-model calibration. The impact is significant: it allows organizations to deploy robust summarization pipelines even when using black-box APIs or legacy models, ensuring consistent output quality regardless of the generator. Furthermore, the interpretability of the belief graph provides auditability, allowing users to trace why certain edits were made—an essential feature for high-stakes domains like journalism, legal analysis, or healthcare reporting.",
